There is also no rule against being an @#%$, but that doesn't make it any less assinine. I could go to a newbie zone and keep killing all the mobs so none of the newbies get xp. I could kill them faster than they respawn. That is perfectly legal as long as I engage them first. The fact that I wouldn't be breaking any rules doesn't change the fact that I would be acting like a complete and total @#%$.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Play Nice Policy states that:<br>
*edit*<br>
You may not disrupt the normal playability of a zone or area.<br>
Zone/Area Disruption is defined as any activity designed to harm or inconvenience a number of groups rather than a specific player or group of players. This includes things such as:<br>
<br>
Monopolizing most or all of the kills in an area. <br>
*edit*<br>
Wrong, there are rules against being an ass. Here's one of them. <br>
<br>
Outside of the Play Nice rules, there are server conventions, one of which is that if you are ready to go on a quest, and another group is enroute but not there, it's *your* mob, regardless of if they have a level X toon there waiting/camping. <br>
<br>
You are wrong. There was no 'playing the heavy'. There was 'playing by server conventions' and if you don't like them, that's one thing. But don't pretend that abiding by them makes you the bad guy.<br>
<br>
And if ever I was engaged in a race mob, and I lost the race, I wouldn't flame whoever won it. What would be the point of being upset about people playing *by* the rules?<br>
<br>
Sure, I can be annoyed that I lost, but that has nothing to do with the rules of the server. <br>
<br>
If group A wasn't fast enough to beat group B, that has nothing to do with the conventions the server operates under. It has everything to do with the ability of group B to move faster. <br>
<br>
Would anyone support a system by which Group A gets an extra half hour if they didn't have a wizard or druid with them? Should we make group B wait because they got there faster? <br>
<br>
I really hope you can see that distinction, if none other.<br>
<br>
Yers,<br>
