<br>
You keep going on and on about server convention and how it was followed. My point is that just following the server conventions is nothing to be proud of. It may in fact be something to ashamed of, depending on circumstance.<br>
<br>
Do you remember when there were no limits on the number of &quot;friends&quot; from any particular guild joining another guild on its reserved day in a plane? There were people who took advantage of the situation to get multiple bookings of the planes. There was nothing wrong with that according to the server convention of the time, yet it was still wrong. Or are you going to argue that? There is a reason the rules have since changed.  <br>
<br>
It is possible to follow server convention and still do something wrong. Your argument seems to be that as long as someone follows server convention, they haven't done anything wrong. <br>
<br>
My point, in language as concise and clear as possible: Following server convention is the absolute minimum expected from anyone. Doing so is nothing to be proud of. There may be situations where doing so is actually something to be ashamed of. I think this is one of those. As I mentioned earlier, it is the MINIMUM expected of us.<br>
<br>
I agree with you completely that Chop should not have killed the mob.  <br>
<br>
What does the server convention regarding &quot;race&quot; mobs mean? Quite explicitly, it means &quot;might makes right&quot;. If you have the force, it is yours. While this may work well at the guild/multi group level for high end, contested mobs, it isn't something that works well for single group mobs. It just doesn't. Here is an example why.<br>
<br>
