Tek<br>
<br>
<br>
* the &quot;will of the Rathe&quot; being defined as the group of guilds making up the RTA that have taken it upon themselves to govern the rules, rotations, lists, and conventions of The Rathe Server.<br>
<br>
** Chopstickz reasons to take the action he(she) did continue to remain unknown to us.  Although many have presented the &quot;FACT&quot; of why they think he(she) did this, it is mere conjecture.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uroggulbuk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Roggulbuk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Toede Slavedriver</span><br>  Posts: 564<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(6/5/02 4:13:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=569.topic&index=89>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Chops</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I think Chops was a d!ck for killing the mob, but I totally see where he is coming from having moved servers entirely because of my disgust with bullying behavior such as this.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, it's wrong to play by the rules? <br>
<br>
It's bullying if you get there faster, but someone else wants it, is that right? <br>
<br>
I want the frenzy camp for my group, but there's another group there already, who are capable of holding the area. What ever shall we do? On the server *I* think we play on, you leave and try again another time. <br>
<br>
But wait... what if that group that is capable of holding the area isn't a group any more, and not capable of holding the spawn? What if that 'group' is instead a level 50 monk? Should the group that is ready to go *not* take frenzy because someone else wants it? <br>
<br>
If that's the case, from now on, frenzy is mine and mine alone, based only on the simple truth that... I want it. Since it is obviously bullying to take something from me that I want, especially if I was there first regardless of my ability to actually do anything with it, you'll have to recognize that I have at least, oh, an hour to gather up the groupmates that I want so I can move in.<br>
<br>
Look, the bottom line is that if you are going to say this...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I must say we are very blessed on the Rathe to have such a civilized society that come together for the greater good<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
you also have to realize that sometimes people are going to 'lose' the race. Chopstickz lost, and no matter if Jagg was in United Necro's, or BotS or unguilded, he and his friends got there first. <br>
<br>
And if you are going to say this...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I agree with you completely that Chop should not have killed the mob. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
it is not consistant to then say that this statement...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
yes i agree. thus when you see you cant kill a mob that takes a group and another group enters to do the turn in and kill it, YOU DONT KILL THE TURN IN MOB. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
is wrong. If you believe that the quest mob should have been left alone, then you believe that it should not have been killed. Since, left up, Jagganath would have been able to do the quest, you either have to say that chopstickz was right in preventing everyone from doing the quest, or that Jagganath should have been able to proceed, because by the conventions, Jagg won. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Your argument seems to be that as long as someone follows server convention, they haven't done anything wrong. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Actually, my argument doesn't <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>seem</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to be that at all. That is my argument *exactly*. You cannot say that someone is doing something wrong by *not* breaking a server convention, because they aren't doing anything that runs contrary to the general position of the server. <br>
<br>
Look, it's quite simple. What is the server convention? The group with the sufficent force there first, gets to try the mob. <br>
<br>
Does that convention not apply when there is someone else involved? Is the convention therefore &quot;If you are there first, and with a sufficent force, and no one else is there, you can try the mob&quot;? No, it's not. <br>
<br>
You can't punish people for obeying the rules. You can't say that sometimes it is wrong to follow the conventions. Here's why:<br>
<br>
If it were wrong to follow conventions at times, in the way they are designed, than they could be broken by anyone, at any time. If conventions do not work for anyone, then they will stop working for everyone. <br>
<br>
If, for example, Chopstickz had shown up second, but with a kill force, it would have been his kill. Targetting the 'ubers' and saying &quot;oh, well, they should have waited another half hour/hour/two hours for Chopstickz to gather forces&quot; what incentive are we offering them to follow the conventions? <br>
<br>
None, that's what. <br>
<br>
In the real world, this quote is designed to illustrate the blind neutrality of the legal system.<br>
<br>
&quot;The law, in its magestic equality, forbids both the rich and the poor to beg in the streets, live under bridges, or steal bread&quot;<br>
<br>
Naturally, this is meant to show that while the law forbids it for everyone, only one group of people ultimately experiance the application of this law. <br>
<br>
Lets look at what we've established in this situation, however. <br>
<br>
First, we've established that Chopstickz had friends coming, and not far off. <br>
<br>
Second, we've established that shortly after this incident, he was guilded with one of the top three guilds on the server, which to me suggests that he at least knew a few people in a large guild. Logic to that statement: What guild would tag up someone being flamed if he was, on all other accounts, totally unknown to the members? I suggest that not only would chopstickz have had to be known, but would have to be liked by the members of the guild that tagged him. Had this incident happened a week later, this would be an uber vs. uber situation, and the 'unguilded' card could not be played. And unless you want to suggest that the most successful guilds on the server have a completely open recruitment policy, with no prior interaction with potential members, you have to admit that in all liklihood, Chopstickz could have rallied sufficent forces in a reasonable time. <br>
<br>
So you can look at this from one of two directions: The poor unguilded monk that still had a sufficent force en route to the zone only ten minutes slower than one of the major uber guilds on the server, or the monk with people on the way who got all bent out of shape because he lost a race to a mob by ten minutes and killed the quest mob instead. <br>
<br>
The 'poorer getting poorer' situation does not apply here, and I would ask you to logically reason out that it applies *less* to single group encounters than it does to large scale raid encounters.<br>
<br>
I am going to again, be blunt. If you, in 55+ levels, have not made, say, 10 friends online, even though you've been guildless for the entire time, you have not been playing a multiplayer game, and can't really be justified in claiming that you have no friends so you need leeway, when it comes back to bite you in the ass. <br>
<br>
I would suppose that the difficulty a member of a fairly large guild finds in getting 6 people together, is not substantially more difficult than getting 6 people together who are not members of a fairly large guild, or even a guild at all. <br>
<br>
Hell, I remember one day we snagged a level 60 noble blade warrior for a general raid, out of the blue. As long as you have a single teleporting class, you really don't have a huge time dispairity between large guilds and unguilded. <br>
<br>
Do you really believe that an *entire* uber guild is going to mobalize on a single Angry Goblin spawn? <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
My point is that just following the server conventions is nothing to be proud of. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
First off all, that's an attitude born of playing on the server for a time. No, no one expects praise for *not* stealing, in real life, obviously, because it's expected that you will not steal. However, where in the game, there is *nothing* to force you to maintain server conventions other than the knowledge that it is better if you do so, for everyone, then following server conventions becomes worthwhile, even if it is not in your self interest at that moment<br>
<br>
I will refine the argument that you put forward: Sometimes, it is *nice* of people to break with conventions and say &quot;well, technically it is our mob, but you can have it, good luck&quot;. But no one is obligated to do that, nor should they be, as you are suggesting, Graal. If the system is broken, it would be very obvious, as you illustrate with your example of the unlimited guests to the planes scenario you present. A very broken system would be something which *forced* an obligation above and beyond server conventions on certain people, or certain groups of people. <br>
<br>
However, as Livius pointed out to me, making misleading comparisons does not prove your argument, in fact, it weakens it. <br>
<br>
You have cited a problem situation, one which was rectified. Are you claiming that the current rules to a race mob are wrong? What then, would your alternative be? Instead of 'first group to the mob with force' would you say 'first group to the mob with force, unless the guild has more than 40 level 60's in it, in which case, they have a minimum waiting time of 2 hours, to allow others to show up'?<br>
<br>
If you are going to claim that conventions are subjective, then why have them at all? If they do not apply as equally to an unguilded player as they do a guilded one, obviously one of those two groups is going to remove themselves from the arrangement, and I wouldn't blame them. <br>
<br>
So what's the end result?<br>
<br>
Do you still think that the winners of a race should *always* wait for anyone else to show, and then what? random on who gets the mob? No, naturally not, because that removes the purpose of a race mob, right?<br>
<br>
You obviously don't think that the winners should *never* wait for anyone else to show, you encourage people to wait or give the spawn up, in fact. That's certainly admirable, but really, that's kindness above and beyond what the community describes for the situation. Example: My partner at work, her apartment burned two nights ago. I am not obligated to offer to pay her bills with my check while she tries to buy new clothes and food with hers. It would, however, be nice of me, but I'm not under *any* obligation to do so. Would you say I was 'in the wrong' if she asked me for 800 bucks and I said &quot;no&quot;? <br>
<br>
Jagganath had no obligation to a player he didn't know, other than prescribed by the server rules, because *those* are the rules that we abide by. <br>
<br>
You can't say he was doing something wrong by wanting something for himself, and you can't say that he *has* to put himself second or lower in line, just because someone else wants it. If that was the case, why don't you say that Chopstickz was wrong in wanting something for himself, and *he* has to put himself second or lower in line, just because someone else wants it.<br>
<br>
I suspect that if big bad BotS had been beaten by little ol Chopstickz, and *they* had killed the turn in mob, that your attitude would be totally differant. I suspect that you would be laying a heavy blame then. <br>
<br>
And so would I.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> There was nothing wrong with that according to the server convention of the time, yet it was still wrong.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Because you brought it up: Wrong how?<br>
Because it was exploiting the intent of the system? Because it wasn't intended to let people book multiple days in a row? I'd say you'd have to be pretty convincing to deny that it was changed because it made things *un*fair. <br>
<br>
So ask yourself: what's the intent of the system?<br>
<br>
To allow a group/raid to have an uninterupted chance at a mob, no matter who the group is, or is made up of, as long as they were there first and could have a *chance* to win. (Claim that the chance is irrelevent, and I swear I will try to claim Trakanon with 10 level one players)That sounds a whole lot differant than the example you are citing, because it is, in fact, completely differant. Take a page from Livius's book, and use examples that mean something, other than trying to insinuate that there is something very wrong when in fact, it's working nicely until someone doesn't follow the guidelines<br>
<br>
