Either you are purposefully not seeing my point, are unable to see my point, or your standards of human behavior are much lower than mine are. I'm guessing it's option number 1.<br>
<br>
You obviously missed everything I said &quot;minimum acceptable behavior&quot;. Let me spell it out for you:<br>
<br>
It is not against any rule for a boss to be verbally abusive to his employees, yet it is still morally wrong.<br>
<br>
It is not against any rule for someone to walk past a homeless person and tell them to &quot;get a @#%$ job, bum!&quot; yet it is still morally wrong.<br>
<br>
It is not against any rule for a parent to be emotionally abusive to their children, yet it is morally wrong. <br>
<br>
It is not against any rule for a teacher to be emotionally abusive to the children in his/her class, yet it is still morally wrong.<br>
<br>
It is not against any rule for a person to use trickery to sell a product that doesn't live up to the expectations he/she created in the customer, yet it is still morally wrong.<br>
<br>
Here is a nice example...it is not against any rule for a wealthy person to travel to a nation in the middle of a famine and use their wealth to buy up all available food, then have it burned. Would you consider that morally wrong?<br>
<br>
Is the point obvious enough now? If all you aspire to is the minimum acceptable standards of behavior, don't expect people to applaud you for it.<br>
