<br>
So perhaps you'd better rethink the position as not <br>
&quot;aspir{ing} to is the minimum acceptable standards of behavior&quot; but rather *expecting those standards from another player*. Oh, what a horrible idea, eh? To think that another player might *gasp* live up to the same minimum acceptable standards of behavior. Whatever would we do, if the server was filled with conventions based around that very thing...<br>
<br>
If it was NB and BotS in a race for, say, mob X, how would you handle that dispute?<br>
<br>
Lets say that there was 1 NB in the zone for 5 hours, and then BotS got there in force, followed 30 minutes later by a force of NB. How would you call that conflict? Neither party has done anything wrong at this point, morally or otherwise, they both just want to kill the same mob, or do the same quest. <br>
<br>
Would you say that NB gets to do it because they had one person in the zone already? That's pretty easy going of you, if that indeed would be your answer.<br>
<br>
So yeah, let me just make it a little more obvious why the harping on minimum acceptable standards is getting kinda old, and irrelevant:<br>
<br>
When Chopstickz and Jagg both wanted to kill the goblin, neither one had done anything wrong, morally or otherwise, not by server standards, not by Play Nice Policy Standards. <br>
<br>
Jagg had a force present to kill it. By server standards, bringing a force to engage a mob doesn't seem wrong to me. By the play nice policy standards, neither person had turned in the quest note, so therefore, neither one had claim to the resultant spawn. Hmmm, no *wrong* behavior yet.<br>
<br>
Oh, wait, right, here comes the wrong behavior... Chopstickz kills the quest mob! Right, I knew that came somewhere about here in the story. Well, lets see: that violates the server standards of losing by the rules and not being a d!ck about them...oh, and look, it violates the Play Nice Policy and it's quest interferance part too. <br>
